               <p>194. <persName id="def1-194-18341124" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def1-194-18341124" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-194-18341124" type="surname" value="REED"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-194-18341124" type="given" value="SAMUEL"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">SAMUEL REED</hi>
                  </persName> was indicted<rs id="t18341124-194-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18341124-194-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18341124-194-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="receiving"></interp> for receiving, on the <rs id="t18341124-cd-189" type="crimeDate">
                        <join result="offenceCrimeDate" targOrder="Y" targets="t18341124-194-offence-1 t18341124-cd-189"></join>10th of Sep<lb></lb>tember</rs>, 46lbs. weight of hay, value 2<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.; the property of <persName id="t18341124-name-1401" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18341124-name-1401" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18341124-name-1401" type="surname" value="MARFLEET"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18341124-name-1401" type="given" value="STEPHEN"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18341124-194-offence-1 t18341124-name-1401"></join>Stephen Marfleet</persName>, well knowing it to have been stolen.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18341124-name-1402" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18341124-name-1402" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18341124-name-1402" type="surname" value="LOXTON"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18341124-name-1402" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>JAMES LOXTON</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">police-constable P</hi> 236.) On the 18th of September, I was watching, at a quarter before eight o'clock, at the Greyhound public-house, Clapham-road—Osgood, who has been convicted, drove up in a horse and cart—he got out, put the nose-bag on the horse, and then opened the door at the back of the cart, and this prisoner pulled out a bundle of hay, about 46lbs. weight—he took it into the stable, followed by Osgood and another man, carrying a sack with some corn in it, which had also been taken from the cart—I followed them, and saw the prisoner throw the hay under a stair-case in the stable—I took him into custody—he struggled violently and got from me—he seized a pitch-fork, made a thrust at me, and said, "D—n your eyes, now come on, I will not be taken"—he got away then, but on a subsequent occasion I took him—he refused to go till I told him the charge, and he resisted very much—I called two brother officers, and he was taken.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner.</hi> I was called to give the horse some water, and while I was doing that, another man took the corn—I took the hay, but I did not know it had been stolen—the other officer told him to knock the b—r down. <hi rend="italic">Witness</hi>. No; my brother officer said, "Knock him down," which I should have done—but I could not get at him for the fork.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18341124-name-1403" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18341124-name-1403" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18341124-name-1403" type="surname" value="MARFLEET"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18341124-name-1403" type="given" value="STEPHEN"></interp>STEPHEN MARFLEET</persName>
                  </hi>. William Osgood was my con<lb></lb>victed for stealing this hay at the last Sessions.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18341124-name-1404" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18341124-name-1404" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18341124-name-1404" type="surname" value="TWOAT"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18341124-name-1404" type="given" value="GEORGE"></interp>GEORGE TWOAT</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">police-constable P</hi> 18.) I went into the stable, and saw the prisoner throw the hay off—I was engaged with Osgood and the other prisoner, who have been convicted—I called to Loxton to knock the prisoner down, but not till he had got the fork, and I thought he would run him through.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner.</hi> I said I would go any where. <hi rend="italic">Witness.</hi> No; you said you would not be taken, and you took the fork up—there were four of them there, and the prisoner escaped.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">JURY</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> What was the prisoner? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I believe he was under-ostler—the ostler has been convicted.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18341124-name-1405" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18341124-name-1405" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18341124-name-1405" type="surname" value="EDMONDS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18341124-name-1405" type="given" value="EDWARD"></interp>EDWARD EDMONDS</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a clerk to Mr. Lewis, the attorney. I was present at the trial of Skelton, who was ostler and occupier of this stable—it was sworn on the trial, by the policeman, that he directed three per<lb></lb>sons to take the hay into his stable, as they supposed Osgood would re<lb></lb>turn from town there to feed his horses—I have seen the stable, and the place in which this hay was thrown is not an improper place to put it into—Skelton was acquitted, and it appeared that this prisoner is one who hangs about as a cad, to get a shilling of any passengers who call there.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">to</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">LOXTON</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> You say, upon the cart driving up, the prisoner went to the back of the cart, and pulled out the hay? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes—Skelton was not at the cart, but I believe he was about there—he had not an op<lb></lb>portunity</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183411240218"></xptr>
               <p>of speaking to the prisoner between the time of the cart driving up, and his taking the hay.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">to</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">GEORGE TWOAT</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Did you see the cart drive up? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes—I was within fifty yards of it—I kept my attention on it—Skelton did not communicate with the prisoner after the cart drove up, and before the hay was taken; if he had, I must have seen him.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="largeCaps">
                     <rs id="t18341124-194-verdict-1" type="verdictDescription">
